### Verdict
REQUEST-CHANGES

### Lax-mode filter correctness — INCOMPLETE
Several old-validator-enforced cases are still dropped, and the "always keep required errors" rule is too broad — making some optional fields stricter than old behavior.

### `verifies` regression — REQUIRED FIX
The old validator explicitly enforced:
- QA packet must have a kebab-case string verifies
- Dev packet must not have verifies set

Round 2 suppresses invalid verifies values (QA verifies: null, QA verifies: "Not_KebabCase", dev verifies: "some-dev") because /verifies is optional and not allowlisted. validateIntegrity only checks QA references when verifies !== null, so it does not restore the old schema behavior.

### Compatibility tests — INSUFFICIENT
The added tests cover representative lax-pass cases but do not pin the load-bearing old-fail cases:
- invalid QA/dev verifies
- missing/non-string change_class
- empty/non-string intent spec or spec_path
- feature planned_by: {}
- feature acceptance_criteria item shape
- intent constraints: [""]

### enforcedOptionalPaths allowlist — INCOMPLETE AND PARTLY WRONG
- Missing: packet /verifies; intent /spec and /spec_path need old non-empty-string semantics, not schema presence semantics
- Over-enforced: intent /constraints keeps item minLength; old only required strings

### Other regressions identified
- Feature acceptance_criteria items: old only checked non-empty array; new validates each item (rejects [42] or [""]). Stricter than old.
- Packet change_class: old only checked enum if string-typed; did not require the field. New keeps required + type errors. Stricter than old.
- Intent constraints item minLength: old only required string array. Stricter than old.
- Feature optional planned_by: old didn't check; new keeps nested required errors because required is always kept. Stricter than old.
- Intent spec/spec_path: old used non-empty string presence; new uses property presence via oneOf. Both more-permissive AND stricter cases.

